2) Storms in 2015

storms2015 <- filter(storms, year == 2015)

3) More manipulation

  1. use “dplyr” functions/commands to create a table (e.g. tibble) storm_names_2010s containing columns name and year of storms recorded from 2010 to 2015. To clarify, this table should only contain only one occurrence of each storm. Use head() and tail() to display its first 5 rows, and also its last 5 rows.
storm_names_2010s <- storms %>%
  filter(year >= 2010 & year <= 2015) %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  select(name, year) %>%
  distinct(name, year)

  1. With the entire storms data, use “dplyr” functions/commands to create a table (e.g. tibble) max_wind_per_storm containing three columns: 1) year of storm, 2) name of storm, and 3) max_wind maximum wind speed record (for that storm). Display its first 10 rows, and also its last 10 rows.
max_wind_per_storm <- storms %>%
  group_by(name, year) %>%

4) Some basic plots with “ggplot2”

  1. Make a barchart for the number of (unique) storms in each year during the period 2010 to 2015. Make sure that the axis-label of each bar indicates the associated year. Also, add a meaningful title to the plot.
ggplot(storm_names_2010s, aes(x = year)) + geom_bar() + ggtitle("Count of Unique Storms from 2010 to 2015")

  1. Using the entire storms table, make a density graph for the variable wind, adding color to the border line, as well as the filling color of the density curve. Also, add a meaningful title to the plot. and choose the “Black-White” theme for the background of the graph.
ggplot(storms, aes(x = wind)) + geom_density(fill="blue") + ggtitle("Wind Density Curve") + theme(panel.background=element_rect(color="blue")) + theme_bw()

  1. Make boxplots for the variable pressure of storms in each year during the period 2000 to 2011. Use facets for year (i.e. one facet per year). Also, add a meaningful title to the plot, and choose the “Minimal” theme for the background of the graph.
storms_2000_to_2011 <- storms %>%
  filter(year >= 2000 & year <= 2011)

ggplot(storms_2000_to_2011, aes(x= year, y=pressure)) + geom_boxplot() + facet_wrap(year~.) + ggtitle("Storm Pressure per Year") + theme_minimal() 
## Warning: Continuous x aesthetic -- did you forget aes(group=...)?

  1. Using the entire storms table, graph a timeline of the median wind speed by year. This is: years in the x-axis, median wind-speed in the y-axis, timeline connecting the dots for median wind speed in each year. Also, add a meaningful title to the plot.
med_wind_speeds <- storms %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  mutate(med_wind = median(wind)) %>%
  distinct(year, med_wind)
  
ggplot(med_wind_speeds, aes(x=year, y=med_wind)) + geom_line() + ggtitle("Median Wind Speed Each Year")

5) Wind Speed and Pressure

  1. With the entire storms table, use “ggplot2” functions to make a scatterplot of wind (axis) and pressure (y-axis). Because of the large number of dots, add an alpha value in order to make the dots somewhat transparent. Likewise, see how to add a “smoother” with the function stat.smooth(). Also, add a meaningful title to the plot.
ggplot(storms, aes(x=wind, y=pressure)) + geom_point(alpha=1) + stat_smooth() + ggtitle("Wind vs. Pressure")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

  1. With the entire storms table, use “ggplot2” functions to make the previous scatterplot of wind (x-axis) and pressure (y-axis). This time don’t include a smoother; instead use the variable category to color-code the dots in the scatterplot. Also, add a meaningful title to the plot.
ggplot(storms, aes(x=wind, y=pressure)) + geom_point(aes(color = category)) + ggtitle("Wind vs. Pressure")

6) Storm Categories

  1. Use “dplyr” functions/commands to display, in ascending order, the different (unique) types of storm categories (using the entire storms table).
storms %>%
  group_by(status) %>%
  distinct(status) %>%
  arrange(status)
## # A tibble: 3 × 1
## # Groups:   status [3]
##   status             
##   <chr>              
## 1 hurricane          
## 2 tropical depression
## 3 tropical storm
  1. With the entire storms table, use “dplyr” functions/commands to display a table showing the category, avg_pressure (average pressure), and avg_wind (average wind speed), for each type of storm category. This table should contain three columns: 1) category, 2) avg_pressure, and 3) avg_wind.
storms %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  mutate(avg_wind = mean(wind)) %>%
  mutate(avg_pressure = mean(pressure)) %>%
  distinct(category, avg_pressure, avg_wind) %>%
  arrange(category)
## # A tibble: 7 × 3
## # Groups:   category [7]
##   category avg_wind avg_pressure

## 3 1            70.9         982.
## 4 2            89.4         967.
## 5 3           105.          954.
## 6 4           122.          940.
## 7 5           145.          916.
  1. With the entire storms table, make a chart to visualize pressure in terms of the different category values. For example, you can either use histograms, or density curves, or boxplot, or violin plots. Add a meaningful title to the plot.
ggplot(storms, aes(x = pressure)) + geom_histogram() + ggtitle("Frequency Distribution of Pressure")
